</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Catch This Rising Conservative Star</title>

<body>

<center>
<h2>Catch This Rising Conservative Star</h2>
</center>

Few twenty-six year olds in America today have acheived as much as Leadership Institue graduate and faculty member Kevin Pritchett.<p>

But Kevin Pritchett is no ordinary twenty-six year old.<p>

Culrently the Floor Assistant to Senate Majority Whip Trent Lott, Prikhen has compiled an impressive resume of success as a conservative in the pubiic policy process.<p>

Now Kevin Prhchett  is a rising among young conservative movers and shakers in America<p>

At Dartmouth College Pritchett served as Editor-in-Chief of the well-known and highly successful independent conservative newspaper, <i>The Dartmouth Review</i>. Then,for three years as an intern during his college summers and for two years full-time after college, he worked as a journalist for the <i>Wall Street Journal</i>. Now, in addition to his work as an aide to U.S. Senator Lott, he volunteers as a panelist on <i>Youngbloods</i>, a young-adult version of the McLaughlin Group, broadcast nationally on NET-Political NewsTalk Network.<p>

Kevin Says his wide range of pre-Hill experience along with graduation from a Leadership Institute Capitol Hill Staff Training School in 1988 strengthened his principles and his leadership skills. Now he
helps conservative senators define and set the conservative agenda in the new Congress.<p>

<center>
<h4>Pritchett Active Against Liberal College Establishment</h4>
</center>

Kevin Pritchett became a member of the of Ihe <i>Dartmouth Review</i> to better express his conservative views and to expose the predominately liberal bias on his campus.<p>

Working on <i>The Review</i> helped to strengthen my conservative opinions, says Pritchett. When you have people questioning your views and opinions, then you have to be brave and stick with them to defend them.<p>

<i>The Review</i>, like any other student publication, provides a good forum to exercise your talents and skills, says Pritchett. Dealing with the political controversies related to the paper and the pressure
of your college workload isn't easy, but it will definitely teach you responsibility.<p>

Pritchett ran into his share of troubles early in his association with <i>The Review</i>. One of Dartmouth's most intense racial controversies occurred when writers for <i>The Review</i> raised concerns about a visiting black music instructor  who used very offensive and racist terms in his lectures.  These principled jounalists stood up for their beliefs. But the admhistration's reaction was to defend the offending professor and <b>suspend the <i>Review</i> journalisls from school</b>.
Campus liberals, fomenting a rage against <i>The Review</i>, branded the publication racist.<p>

The heat was on Pritchett, as the first black editor of <i>The Review</i>, he took a stand against the faculty and administration in defense of nis fellow staff members.  He received anonymous death threats
and became an object of scorn by leftist organizaaons. Not surprisingly, these tactics fed his disgust with liberalism and encouraged him to continue working with <i>The Review</i>. In his senior year, as Editor-in Chief, he was a vocal articulate advocate for conservative principles.<p>

<center>
<h4>Pritchett Brings <i>Dartmouth Review</i> Experience to Institute's Student Publications School</h4>
</center>

In 1983, Leadership Instiitute President Morton Blackwell founded the Institute's Student Publications School to train young conservatives how to start their own independent conservative newspapers. The best model was and remains <i>The Dartmouth Review</i>. Kevin Pritchett now serves on the
Institute's Student publications School faculty.<p>

According to students, Pribchett gives a great lecture on investigative reporting. Young joumalists learn how to expose the many injustices which occur every day on college campuses.<p>	

Students running papers on their campuses need to remember that their papers will be more effective if they reveal the idiosyncrasies of the respective administrations and campus groups, says Pritchet. The most effective news is politically active and effects change.<p>

Plitchett continue, The Leadership Institute's Student Publications School teaches students to do just that. It is especially good for students just starting a paper, and it also gives good direction on how to
keep a paper going.<p>

In the summer of 1988, Pritchen served as an intern for Institute Preddent Morton Blackwell. I admire Morton Blackwell for his interest and dedication over a couple of decades of working with young people, says Pritchett. Very few, if any, people have the desire to be involve h the training of young
activists to battle liberals in government and other areas..<p>

<center>
<h4>Pritchett Hired as Writer for the <i>Wall Street Journal</i></h4>
</center>

Also while at Dartmouth, Pritchett worked as an editorial  page intern for <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> for three summers, where he gained valuable experience writing editorial comrnentary. Afler graduation, he continued for two years to write for <i>The Journal</i> full-time in the business and editorial departments. There, Pritchett polished a writing style worthy of envy from his peers. Pritchett plans to return to journalism as a conservative voice after working on Capitol Hill.<p>

<center>
<h4>Pritchett Now a Top Aide to Senate Majority Whip</h4>
</center>

As Floor Assistant to the Majority Whip, Kevin Pritchett is in a prime position to assist not only Senator Trent Lott effectively but also other U.S. Senators.  Pritchett helps write good legislation and fights for its
passage.<p>

Pritchett said the first few months of the Senate were busy with much of their schedule dictated by the House. He doesn't expect the next four months bo be any different. Although the Senate was not bound by the Contract with Amenca, I did a lot of work this year on bills that occurred because
of it, says Pribchett. Social issues did not come up much with the Contract, so I see them coming up in the next few months. Although, I thtnk there will definitely be a big push on the budget.<p>

The challenge will be to get a bill through the Senate which will balance the budget  in the next seven yeas.<p>

With Capibl Hill insiders like Kevin Pritchett working behind the scenes, good public policy can be put into law.<p>

With his expert  knowledge on such a wide range of topics, Pritchett has found himself committed to another ongoing task as a commentator on Paul Weyrich's NET-Political NewsTalk Network show, <i>Youngbloods</i>.<p>

Youngbloods ia a call-in talk show of both conservatives and liberals in the twenty-something age range designed to counteract the stereotypical view of the MTV generation with a group of young commentators who discuss political issues.<p>

Pritchett finds <i>Youngbloods</i> as a way to help young adults express their views and be taken seriously.  We talk about issues that affect everything, and what government is doing or should be doing, says Pritchett.<p>

<center>
<h4>Institute Graduate Ahead of the Game</h4>
</center>

Because of his many activities during and after college, Kevin Pritchett has strengthened his conservative views and become a leader at the forefront of the conservative movement.  The type of guidance and instruction Pritchett got working for Institute President Morton Blackwell, <i>The Dartmouth Review</i>, <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> and U.S. Senator Trent Lott has definitely put him ahead of the political game.<p>

Thanks to the generous support of its many thousands of committed donors, the Leadership Institute has been able to train more than 10,000 young conservatives since its founding.  With continued support, the Leadership Institute can train and place many more conservatives like Kevin Pritchett.<p><p>

[ <a href="i-bl.html">Contents</a> ]
