<head>
<title>New Student Publications Director Leads Free Speech Fight</title>
</head>

<body>

<center>
<h2>New Student Publications Director Leads Free Speech Fight</h2>
</center>

Today's university  climate is alarmingly hoslile toward the traditional  belief on which this nation was founded.<p>

There is plenty of evidence something is amiss in American education
Yale University, long a revered academic institution, lost a huge donation, $20 million, because the liberal faculty administration refused to implement the donor's requested program to emphasize Western Civilization.<p>

There is a fight under way for the heart and soul of America's academic institutions<p>

And Pat Moodey, the Leadership Institute's Student Publications School Director, is no stranger to the  controversy. <p>

In 1991 at Carnegie Mellon University, Mooney was at the center of controversy when he took a principled stand against the liberal campus establishment.   And in two separate, outrageous incidents, Mooney was punished by school officials for his refusal to conforrn to the liberals' far-out political correctness agenda.<p>

<center>
<h4>Insfitute Graduate Sticks to His Strong Moral Beliefs</h4>
</center>

Pat Mooney grew up in Frederick, Maryland.  He says about his upbringing, "Since my mother was forced to flee Cuba, I was raised in a very pro-capitalist, Catholic home. We understood sacrifice and the value of freedom."<p>

Mooney chose to attend Carnegie Mellon for its excellent academic reputation. But he soon learned the university had a liberal agenda to prornote instead.<p>

In October, 1992, he attended the Leadership Institute's Student Publications School learn how to cornbat the campus Left and to start up his own independent conservative newspaper.<p>

<center>
<h4>Graduate Fired for His Beliefs</h4>
</center>

In Mooney's freshman year at Carnegie Mellon, he worked as a Resident Advisor in his dormitory. His.supervisor was impressed with his perforrnance and invited him to continue his job in his sophomore year.<p>

Before the beginning of his sophomore year, Mooney attended a week of training
for RA's.  The controversy began there.<p>

Mooney's area coordinator for student housing passed out pins which promoted
hornosexual rights.  When Mooney declined to wear one, she told him, "You have no choice."<p>

Mooney refused to violate his religious convictions.<p>

So he was fired.<p>

The university's attempt to force him to submit to their liberal  propaganda was an
obvious atlack on Mooney's freedom of religion and speech. So he took the university to court in a federal lawsuit.<p>

After over two years of litigation, Carnegie Mellon acknowledged defeat and
offered Mooney a setflement he couldn't refuse.<p>

Mooney remarks, "I am very, very pleased with the outcome."<p>

During the debate on Mooney's dismissal, the liberal campus paper blasted him as a "homophobic bigot".  Mooney realized the ideological vacuum on carnpus was allowing the Left to control the debate. So, with the knowledge he gained from the Leadership Institute, he founded <i>The Phoenix</i>, a conservaffve student publication at CMU, in his junior year.<p>

As a voice for the conservative views on campus, Mooney became a favorite target of radical left  wing attacks.<p>


<center>
<h4>Money Attacked for Protesting Liberal Sllander</h4>
</center>

In his senior year, Mooney was disgusted by a poster from a carnpus gay-rights group which attacked the Catholic church.  The poster defamed Cardinal John O'Connor and compared him to a  condom with the slur, "Know your scumbags."<p>

A visiting professor argued the poster deserved the university's support.  When Mooney dared to question the decency of this bigoted and hateful attack on Catholics, he was accused of haras ment.<p>

For refusing to give in to the liberal adminislrators, Mooney was attacked as a homophobic religious fanatic. The liberal campus newspaper immediately defended the professor's position.  And the Dean of Student Affairs advised the professor to press charges against Mooney.<p>

<center>
<h4>Kangaroo Court Passes Sentence on Preposterous Charges</h4>
</center>

In the kangaroo court which followed, Pat Mooney was faced with possible suspenion and even expulsion.  Mooney was also charged with violating the university's confidentiality rules because he spoke with the press about the ordeal.  When Mooney's lawyer explained his client had no knowledge of these rules and inquired about the universty's confidentiality laws, he was told, "They're confidential."<p>

Furthermore, Mooney was officially gagged during the deliberations of the disciplinary committee.  His lawyer argued the university provided no due process and questioned their right to threaten his free speech rights.<p>

The committee ruled Mooney did not harass the visiting professor and dismissed
the charge along with two others. It did, however, find him guilty of violating the free
speech rights of the group which posted the flier by removing it.  His sentence was 
indefinite probation.<p>

Pat Mooney successfully appealed the decision tothe university president, who reduced it to a warning.<p>

<center>
<h4>Mooney's Injustice Received Nationwide Coverage</h4>
</center>
 
The case garnered the media's attention, includng the <i>Washington Times</i> and <i>U.S. News and World Report</i>.  Pat Mooney was widely hailed for refusing to succumb to the vicious forces of political correctness which have captured so many campuses today.<p>

Now, Mooney looks back with great satisfaction at the outcome.  He used the skills he devloped at Leadership Institute schools to gain support for his fight and ultimately to win the battle.<p>

Mooney has great faith in the potential of independent conservative campus newspapers on campuses where the news would otherwise be one-sided.<p>
	
<h4>Conservatlve College Journalists Have Great Power  In Their Camus Papers</h4>

As the Leadership Institute's Publications School Director, Mooney is in a positon  influence greatly the debate campuses today.  His job is to encourage the proliferation of conservative college papers.<p>

"Conservative journalisls," Mooney observes, "bring to light the scandals and excesses of liberal admhistrators and college professors who normally hide behind the cloak of academic freedom."<p>

He attributes his perseverance to his faith, guidance and friends.  He is the first to say the training he received from the Leadership Institute gave him the tools and connections to win  his fight against the liberal campus establishment.<p>

Every year the Leadership lnstitute trains many college activists to battle the double standards invoked by politically correct university adminstrators.  The Institute's Student Publictions School has now trained 785 young conservatives.  One hundred conservative campus papers publish at American universities.<p>

With the generouis and faithful support of Institute donors, every year more and more activists are trained to defend the rights and principles which Americans hold dear.<p><p>

