<p>
<i>June 1996</I>
<P>
<H2><B>CONTENTS</B><BR></H2>
<OL>
<LI><a href="#gun">Gun Control: Is the Tide Turning?</a><BR>
<UL>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#debate">The Debate Packs A Lot of Heat</a><BR>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#nra">The National Rifle Association</A><BR>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#gun"> Gun Owners of America</a><BR>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#cit"> Citizens Committee for the Right to Keep and Bear Arms</a>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#hand">Handgun Control Inc.</a>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#coal">Coalition to Stop Gun Violence</a>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#viol">Violence Policy Center</a>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#state">The States Lead the Way</a>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#memb">Members of the Coalition to Stop Gun Violence</a>
<DD><DD><LI><a href="#stat">States that have passed CCW reform since 1987</a>
</UL>
<LI><a href="#arm">Denigrating America's Armed Forces<BR></a>
</ol>
<P>
<a name="gun">
<BR>
<b>Gun Control:  Is the Tide Turning?</B><BR>
<I>Battleground Shifts to the States</I><P>

<DD>Gun control is one of our society's most contentious issues.  It 
arouses strong opinions and inflames emotions on both sides of a debate that 
has become inextricably linked to concerns about crime.  Both factions in the debate see 
crime as central to their respective arguments.  
Does the availability of firearms contribute to crime? 
 Or does gun control leave law-abiding citizens defenseless against armed criminals? 
 Much more is at stake than the answers to these questions.  For some, guns are a 
symbol of all that is wrong with our 
violence-prone society; for others, gun-ownership is a 
fundamental right, an indispensable element of a free society.  
<DD>Much of the gun control debate has focused on the edges of the issue, as the 
opposing sides try to define the limits of the country's acceptance of firearms.  In 
recent years, attention has been focused on gun control measures at the national level.  
In 1993, after seven years of lobbying, Handgun Control, Inc. finally succeeded in pushing 
the so-called &quot;Brady Bill&quot; to passage.  The bill, named after former White House Press Secretary James Brady, mandates a five-day 
waiting period between purchase and delivery of a handgun.  A year later, as part of the 
1994 Crime Bill, Congress passed a ban on the importation and domestic manufacture of 
a number of semi-automatic firearms, so-called &quot;assault weapons.&quot;  Anger over the 
passage of these two pieces of legislation helped 
fuel the backlash against congressional Democrats that led to Republicans taking control 
of Congress for the first time in forty years.
<a name="debate">
<P><B>The Debate Over Concealed Weapons Packs A Lot of Heat</B>
<P>
<DD>Despite gun control activists' success in tightening gun laws at the national level, 
a broad-based and little-noticed movement has been working in the states to liberalize 
restrictive gun laws.  This &quot;Quiet Revolution&quot; in the states has focused primarily on 
changing state laws to allow individuals to carry 
a loaded, concealed firearm.  
<DD>In 1987, Florida became the first state in recent times to relax its concealed 
weapon laws.  Shortly thereafter, a number of 
other states followed suit, and the trend continues. 
 In 1995 alone, ten states liberalized their requirements.  Most of these states now 
have what is known as a &quot;shall-issue&quot; 
system, under which applicants are deemed to have a right to obtain a CCW (Carrying 
Concealed Weapon) permit, and the state must 
provide an affirmative reason to deny the issuance 
of one.  For example, states may deny applicants who have prior felony convictions or a 
history of mental illness.  They may also require proof of a certain level of proficiency with 
a handgun.
<DD>Naturally, such changes have not come without considerable controversy.  
Opponents of the Florida measure predicted carnage in the streets and suggested that 
the state's new moniker would be the 
&quot;GUNshine State.&quot;  One hysterical newspaper 
editorial summed up fears about the new law:  
<blockquote><I>&quot;[A] pistol-packing citizenry will mean 
itchier trigger fingers . . . South Florida's climate of 
 smoldering fear would flash like napalm when every stranger totes a piece, and 
every mental snap in traffic could lead to the 
crack of gunfire.&quot;</I></blockquote>  
<DD>The facts paint a far less frightening picture.  Handgun Control, Inc. (HCI) 
argues that CCW reform &quot;has not made Florida 
a safer place.&quot;  While conceding that the 
homicide rate has decreased, HCI observes that violent crime in Florida increased by 
17.8 percent in the five years following enactment of CCW reform.  But this tells only part of 
the story.  While violent crime did increase in Florida, it rose by 22.3 percent 
nationally, noticeably higher than the jump in Florida.  
In addition, fears of legally licensed firearms carriers turning minor disputes into 
deadly confrontations proved baseless.  Of 314,938 licenses issued since the law went into 
effect, only 470 have been revoked for any reason.  
<DD>Contrary to the assertions of anti-gun lobbyists, the evidence indicates that an 
armed citizenry generally has a deterrent effect 
on crime.  According to sociologists James Wright and Peter Rossi, criminals tend to 
be more concerned about encountering an armed victim than about being arrested by the 
police.  Wright and Rossi conducted two studies commissioned by the U.S. Department 
of Justice in the 1980s that examined the attitudes of incarcerated criminals towards 
violent crime.  They interviewed over 1,800 convicted felons who were in prison in ten 
different states.  A majority of these felons 
claimed to worry more about dealing with an armed victim while committing a crime than 
about running into the police.  That's one reason why so many crimes are committed 
outside the home:  criminals fear armed homeowners. 
 And when criminals do target houses, they pick residences where no one is home 
to avoid the possibility of being shot at.  Criminals prefer preying on people on the streets: 
 thanks to concealed weapons restrictions, they will most likely be unarmed.  
<DD>Wright and Rossi's study seems to validate the common assumption that 
civilian gun ownership has a significant deterrent effect on criminal behavior.  Thirty-four 
percent of the felons interviewed indicated that at some point in their criminal careers 
they had been &quot;scared off, shot at, wounded, 
or captured by an armed victim.&quot;  
<DD>How often do private citizens use firearms for self defense?  It is difficult to 
obtain precise figures, since many of these uses 
are never reported to the police, but research by Florida State University criminologist Gary Kleck provides some insight.  Dr. Kleck 
undertook a huge study in 1992-93, asking nearly 5,000 people detailed questions about 
whether or not they had used a firearm to protect themselves from crime, and if so under 
what circumstances.  From the results of this 
study, Kleck estimated that close to 2.5 million Americans annually actually use firearms 
for self-defense.  In the vast majority of these cases, no one is killed or wounded, and 
rarely are shots even fired.  
<DD>It is generally recognized that localities with the strictest gun control laws do 
not have lower crime rates than jurisdictions with less restrictive laws.  For example, the 
District of Columbia has probably the strictest 
gun control laws of any municipality, and it has 
an extremely high crime rate.  Neighboring Virginia, with relatively few gun control 
laws (and a shall-issue system for CCW since 1995), has a much lower crime rate. 
<P>
<a name ="nra">
<B>National Rifle Association</B>
<P>
<DD>The participants in the political debate over concealed weapons are familiar 
and their positions are predictable.  What's different is the political strategy that 
opponents of gun control are using.  Increasingly 
frustrated by gridlock in Washington, groups like the National Rifle Association have 
turned their sights on the states, and they have 
had remarkable success in changing laws once considered politically unalterable.  Of 
these laws, CCW reform is the most recent and perhaps the most significant change.  
<DD>The largest, most powerful and probably best-known organization is the National 
Rifle Association (NRA).  Founded in 1871 by a number of ex-Union army officers to 
promote civilian marksmanship, the NRA has grown to over three million members 
nationwide, and it has an annual budget of nearly 
$155 million (1993 figures).  The NRA is a 
501(c)(4) organization, as is its lobbying division, 
the Institute for Legislative Action (ILA).  This means it is tax-exempt but, because it is 
organized to influence legislation, contributions to it are not tax-deductible.  The NRA has 
an affiliated PAC, the NRA Political Victory Fund, and a number of affiliated 501(c)(3) 
organizations, including the NRA Foundation, Firearms Civil Rights Legal Defense Fund, 
International Shooter Development Fund, National Firearms Museum Fund, and the 
NRA Special Contribution Fund.  In the 1993-94 election cycle, the NRA's PAC 
contributed almost $6 million to congressional 
candidates of both parties across the country  The ILA itself spent another $2 million on 
mailings, phone banks, and other benefits to pro-gun 
candidates. 
<DD>For most of its existence, the NRA concerned itself with training people in the 
safe and proper usage of firearms and in sponsoring shooting competitions.  This began 
to change in the late 1960s as increasingly restrictive gun control laws were proposed 
and passed, most notably the Gun Control Act of 1968.  For a time, there was 
considerable debate within the NRA about whether 
increasing the group's focus on political issues was compatible with its traditional 
interest in promoting marksmanship.  This debate continued through the 1970s, and 
culminated in the &quot;Cincinnati Revolt&quot; in which 
the NRA's executive vice-president and a number of board members who favored a 
less active political role were replaced by politically-oriented activists who wanted to 
fight gun-control legislation.  
<DD>The NRA is actively lobbying at the national, state, and local levels.  Working 
in conjunction with state organizations, NRA has successfully pushed for CCW reform 
in 19 states, and it is close to passing 
legislation in several others, including Missouri 
and New Mexico.  In this effort, the NRA works closely with sportsmen's organizations, 
including hunting and target shooting clubs, as well as with crime victims' groups.  In 
the field of CCW reform, NRA has so far worked exclusively at the state level, entirely 
bypassing the U.S. Congress.  NRA is lobbying for the adoption of laws at the state level 
that are patterned on Florida's CCW law, which establishes a shall-issue system placing 
some basic requirements on license holders..
<DD>Following the death of NRA President Tom Washington in 1995, First 
Vice-President Marion Hammer assumed office, 
giving the NRA its first-ever woman president.  
The former president of Unified Sportsmen of Florida, Hammer was instrumental in 
lobbying the Florida legislature for the passage 
of the state's CCW reform in 1987.  Hammer is a life-long Democrat and a grandmother 
who has already purchased firearms for her three grandchildren.  
<DD>It is perhaps not coincidental that the NRA's president and its chief lobbyist, 
Tanya Metaksa, are women at a time when the organization has begun to emphasize the 
importance of training women in the use of firearms. 
 This new emphasis underscores the NRA's traditional interest in firearms training.  But 
it also seeks to enlist women as a new political constituency to the ranks of those who 
believe the possession of firearms is a crime deterrent. 
<P>
<a name="gun">
<B>Gun Owners of America</B>
<P>
<DD>The other major national organization pushing for CCW reform is a more recent arrival 
to the gun control debate.  Founded in 1977 by former California state Senator H. L. 
&quot;Bill&quot; Richardson, Gun Owners of America 
presents itself as &quot;the no-compromise gun lobby,&quot; and its position on CCW reflects that.  
<DD>In contrast to NRA, Gun Owners is pushing for adoption of handgun carry laws 
modeled after those in effect in Vermont.  Alone among the states, Vermont does not 
require a permit of any sort to carry a concealed handgun.  State law makes it a crime to 
&quot;carr[y] a dangerous or deadly weapon, openly 
or concealed, while committing a felony.&quot;  
Gun Owners calls current CCW reform legislation &quot;phony,&quot; and it opposes concealed 
carry laws that require any &quot;government 
approval, permission, license, or tax&quot; to obtain a 
permit to carry a concealed weapon.  Gun Owners argues that the CCW reform legislation 
that has been adopted by most states discriminates against the poor and minorities 
because it requires application fees and the cost of firearms training that states require 
for certification to carry.  More importantly, Gun Owners argues that any government 
regulation of firearms possession will inevitably lead to further restrictions as well as 
violate constitutional rights guaranteed by the 
Second Amendment.
<DD>Politically, Gun Owners is outside of what is usually considered the political 
mainstream; it is not concerned about angering the 
political establishment.  Gun Owners has been willing to endorse and support 
candidates for public office who are considered 
longshots with little chance of winning.  In 1994, 
for instance, Gun Owners, unlike the NRA, enthusiastically backed Republican 
Steve Stockman in his congressional race against longtime House Judiciary Committee 
Chairman Jack Brooks (D-TX).  Brooks had angered Gun Owners by working for passage 
of the 1994 Crime Bill, which contained a ban on the importation and manufacture of 
certain kinds of military-style firearms known as 
&quot;assault weapons.&quot;  Gun Owners had no 
compunction about challenging Brooks, a powerful member of Congress who had 
enormous influence over gun control legislation.  Stockman went on to defeat Jack Brooks and 
became one of the &quot;Giant Slayers&quot; of the 
1994 congressional election.
<DD>Gun Owners has had limited success promoting its preferred version of CCW reform. 
 Despite the many states considering reform legislation, Gun Owners has not 
convinced any to enact its purer version.  Gun 
Owners remains an outsider, occasionally scoring a policy success, but mainly working to 
influence the course and scope of the gun control debate.       
<a name="cit">
<P>
<B>Citizens Committee for the Right to Keep and Bear Arms</B>
<P>
<DD>Also involved in the debate is the Citizens Committee for the Right to Keep and 
Bear Arms, and its affiliated 501(c)(3), the 
Second Amendment Foundation.  Citizens Committee is headquartered in Bellevue, 
Washington, and employs John Snyder, an active political foe of gun control since the 1960s, 
as a congressional lobbyist in Washington, DC.  Citizens Committee was originally 
founded as a committee of the Young Americans for Freedom, but later became independent.
<a name="hand">
<P>
<B>Handgun Control Inc.</B>
<P>
<DD>Anti gun groups have scored notable legislative successes in recent years.  In 
1994, following the election of Bill Clinton, they secured federal legislation placing 
restrictions on handgun purchases and banning so-called assault weapons.  However, 
the gun control groups have had few successes in the latest state legislative battles over 
the right to carry concealed weapons.  Like many other big government advocacy groups, 
their power is concentrated in Washington, DC.  They thrive on coalition-building and 
on public relations imagemaking in the national media.  The real question is whether 
these advantages can survive renewed grassroots challenges by state and local defenders 
of Second Amendment rights.   
<DD>The largest and most powerful opponent of CCW reform is the 501(c)(4) 
Handgun Control, Inc. and its affiliated 501(c)(3), 
the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence.  Compared to the NRA, HCI is a new arrival 
in Washington.  It was founded as the National Council to Control Handguns in 1974 
by Mark Borinsky, a community activist who was mugged by an assailant who used 
a handgun.  Borinsky was joined in 1975 by Pete Shields, a former DuPont 
executive, whose son was the last of the victims of 
the infamous &quot;Zebra Killer.&quot;  Shields 
became executive director of NCCH in 1976. 
<DD>In 1985, the Council (renamed Handgun Control in 1978) gained a new board 
member who gave the group a much higher profile.  Sarah Brady's involvement in the gun 
control movement came about in a very public way:  her husband James Brady, 
Ronald Reagan's press secretary, was shot and almost killed in the 1981 attempt on 
the President's life.  Brady's name soon became synonymous with HCI's flagship 
legislative accomplishment, the Brady Bill, a federal 
law which mandates a nationwide waiting period of five business days before the purchaser 
of a handgun can take possession of it.  
<DD>Since its founding, HCI has grown to over 380,000 members, and it has an annual 
budget of over $6 million.  The affiliated Center 
to Prevent Handgun Violence (CPHV) had a budget in 1994 of $2.4 million, which 
mainly funds educational programs ($1.3 million) and a legal action project ($430,000).  
CPHV's educational efforts include its STAR 
(Straight Talk About Risks) program, which is 
intended to convince school-aged children that 
guns are a key  element of criminal violence.  
CPHV also purports to offer safety tips for those who own and keep firearms at home.  
These tips include &quot;EMPTY IT OUT AND LOCK IT UP&quot; and &quot;Explain to children that they 
should NEVER touch guns&quot; (emphasis in the 
original), tips that would preclude the ownership of a firearm for self-protection and the 
imparting of basic gun safety to children.  The advice concludes with the assertion 
that &quot;The safest thing is not to have a gun in 
your home, especially not a handgun.&quot;  
<P>CPHV's Legal Action Project defends gun control legislation in the courts from 
legal challenges by gun rights advocates.  For example, it has filed briefs defending a 
municipal Morton Grove, Illinois law banning handgun ownership and California's 
state ban on assault weapons. 
<DD>The Legal Action Project also has tried to use the courts to secure unlegislated 
gun control.  CPHV has undertaken court cases that would impose a legal doctrine of 
strict liability on manufacturers of so-called 
&quot;assault weapons.&quot;  Under this 
interpretation, manufacturers would be liable for 
damages that result from the misuse of their 
firearms, without regard to the circumstances.  
This back door approach to gun control would effectively end the production of these 
firearms and probably drive the manufacturers out of business.    
<DD>HCI has been very effective at mainstreaming its cause and attracting corporate funding.  In 1993, for example, 
Capital Cities, the owner of the ABC television 
network, and Bell Atlantic, the local telephone monopoly for much of the east coast, 
each gave $5,000 grants to CPHV.  While these are small grants, they give CPHV the 
credibility of an affiliation with major corporations.  
The Capital Cities grant is particularly 
disturbing because gun rights activists have long 
maintained that their point of view is never accurately reported by media outlets such 
as ABC.  When ABC's owner weighs in with what is essentially a political contribution 
to one side of the gun control issue, its capacity for objectivity is seriously in question.            
<DD>In 1986, HCI began what was to become a seven year effort to enact the Brady Bill 
into law.  Shortly after this effort was underway, gun control activists also discovered a 
new target, the so-called assault weapons.  On January 19, 1989, a gunman used a 
semi-automatic version of the Russian AK-47 assault rifle to kill five elementary school 
students and one teacher on a school playground.  Almost overnight, the issue of 
the &quot;widespread availability of 
semi-automatic assault weapons&quot; became a matter of public debate.  Even though the availability and 
use of semi-automatic firearms, almost all of them rifles, with military-style features would 
appear to be a separate issue, &quot;Handgun&quot; 
Control, Inc. quickly took it up with relish. 
<DD>HCI was heartened by the election of Bill Clinton, who was the first president 
since Jimmy Carter to campaign on a platform that included stricter gun control laws.  
Clinton promised to work for passage of both the Brady Bill and an assault weapons ban, 
and in 1994 he fulfilled his promise.  At the 
state level, HCI has been busy opposing CCW reform  but with considerably less 
success. 
<DD>HCI likes to position itself as a 
&quot;moderate&quot; advocacy group pushing for gun control. 
 For the most part it avoids talk of banning guns or adopting other positions that 
might alienate potential supporters.  But after 
the Brady Bill and the assault weapons ban were passed, HCI unveiled &quot;Brady II.&quot;  This was 
its blueprint for national gun control, and it is anything but moderate.  
<DD>Going far beyond the most restrictive state laws, Brady II would mandate federal 
licensing of all handgun owners, registration of 
all handgun sales, and a limit on handgun purchases to one per month.  It would make 
it harder and more expensive to obtain a firearm dealer's license, allow only licensed 
gun dealers to sell ammunition, and make it a 
crime to leave a firearm &quot;accessible&quot; to 
anyone under age 16.  In addition, Brady II would require an &quot;arsenal&quot; license for gun 
collectors; it would ban &quot;non-sporting&quot; 
ammunition, mandate that firearms be made 
&quot;child-proof&quot;, and hold parents liable for 
accidents involving their children's misuse of 
firearms that they own.
<a name="coal">
<P><B>Coalition to Stop Gun Violence</B>
<P>
<DD>If HCI is like the NRA in promoting itself as a &quot;moderate&quot; voice in the gun control 
debate, then the Coalition to Stop Gun Violence (CSGV) is the more hard-core alternative 
for gun control supporters.  Originally called the National Coalition to Ban Handguns, its 
name change illustrates how the group has attempted to widen and obscure its goals. 
 However, unlike HCI, CSGV does not deny that it wants to ban handguns 
completely from &quot;importation, manufacture, sale, 
transfer, ownership, possession and use by the general American public.&quot;  The only 
exceptions it would recognize are the &quot;police, 
military, security officers, and gun clubs where the guns are secured on the club's premises.&quot;  
<DD>Arguing that sporting and recreation is the only legitimate purpose of gun 
ownership, CSGV does not call for an outright ban 
on long arms such as rifles and shotguns (as long as they are not classified as 
&quot;assault weapons&quot;).  But while CSGV supports 
many of the proposals endorsed by HCI, it regards them merely as intermediate steps to its 
ultimate goal of banning handguns.  It would license gun owners and limit handgun 
purchases to one per month for gun owners, limit the availability of gun dealers' licenses 
and raise their cost, increase taxes on handguns and ammunition to pay for health costs 
associated with firearms, and impose its version 
of strict legal liability on firearms 
manufacturers and dealers.  
<DD>CSGV operates on an annual budget of roughly $ 1 million.  Beside its 120,000 
individual members, it has enlisted 46 labor, religious, professional, medical, and 
educational associations as members, including:  
Americans for Democratic Action, the American Jewish Committee, the Center for Science 
in the Public Interest, the National Urban League, the United States Conference of Mayors, 
and the United States Student Association (see page 5 for a full list).
<DD>As with other 501(c)4 lobbying organizations, CSGV has an affiliated 501(c)3 
organization.  This one is called the Educational Fund to End Handgun Violence.  
Established in 1978, the Fund has expanded its activities much like CPHV, operating a program, 
&quot;Hands Without Guns,&quot; for school-aged children.  
Its Firearms Litigation Clearinghouse assists plaintiffs attempting to win damages for 
shooting incidents and for injuries from defective firearms.  It also develops legal theories 
to hold firearms manufacturers liable.  The Fund also hosts an annual conference on 
gun violence and maintains a database of community anti-gun organizations.  It has an 
annual budget of slightly less than $200,000, and receives grants from several 
foundations, including $55,000 from the George Gund 
Foundation and $16,000 from the Kanter Family Foundation.   
<a name="viol">
<P>
<P><B>Violence Policy Center</B>
<P>
<DD>The Violence Policy Center, a think tank for the gun control movement, is the 
newest participant in the policy debate.  Despite 
its small size and lack of recognition, VPC has skillfully disseminated its ideas.  Founded 
in 1988 by activist Josh Sugarmann, VPC has steadily churned out reports and 
publications.  Operating on an annual budget of slightly more than $100,000, the Center 
devotes itself to studying the gun control debate and &quot;educational efforts . . . targeted 
at the general public, public policymakers, and the news media.&quot;  
<DD>While it has examined typical gun control issues such as CCW reform and assault 
weapons, VPC has made the American firearms industry a particular focus of its attention. 
 Indeed, VPC identifies the recent successes of CCW reform as representative of 
legislation conceived to provide &quot;financial 
benefits to all members of the gun lobby.&quot;  In 
<I>Concealed Carry: The Criminal's Companion</I>, VPC argues that the firearms industry, 
faced with stagnant sales, has used CCW reform to expand its markets.  It claims firearms 
instructors believe the training component in CCW reform laws will give them increased 
business.  And it imagines that the NRA sees CCW reform as a way to increase its 
recruitment of members.
<DD>VPC has had a definite impact on the policy debate over gun control.  In 1988, VPC 
published one of the first reports warning against manufacturers of &quot;assault weapons.&quot;  
When the issue acquired national significance, VPC benefitted from the publicity, and it has 
attracted major foundation funding.  Contributions by the John D. and Catherine 
T. MacArthur Foundation, the Joyce Foundation, and the Aaron Diamond 
Foundation suggest the regard in which it is held.  
<a name="state">
<P>
<P><B>The States Lead the Way</B>
<P>
<DD>In late 1994, it looked like gun rights supporters were on the ropes.  With an ally in 
the White House and many supporters in Congress, anti-gun groups had secured 
passage of the Brady Bill and the assault weapons ban, and they were poised to 
accomplish their final goal.  While the anti-gun 
groups tended to work independently of one another, their efforts were dovetailing.  
HCI strove to appear moderate in its calls for federal legislation, and was aided by 
the strident demands of CSGV.  VPC reports and studies provided arguments and data 
for more and stricter gun control laws.
<DD>The election of 1994 stalled the final assault on guns.  But the assault weapons 
ban remains intact, and President Clinton promises to veto any legislation attempting 
a repeal.  Can the anti-gun groups consolidate their gains?
<DD>This may appear to be the current situation at the national level, but it ignores the 
important changes that are taking place at the 
state level.  Reform legislation permitting the 
carrying of concealed weapons is occurring nationwide, and no help from the 
federal government is needed.  Like so many public policy reforms in recent years, from 
school choice to welfare reform, reform has 
&quot;devolved&quot; to the states.  Congress may 
soon get into the act on CCW reform, possibly by considering legislation to allow CCW 
holders to carry guns across state lines.  But for now, however, the federal government is 
not needed for reform to succeed. 
<P>
