<a name="arm">
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Denigrating America's Armed Forces</B><BR>
By Robert V. Pambianco<BR>
<P>
<DD>Lost in the news coverage over the death of Chief of Naval Operations 
Jeremy Boorda, and the concomitant tales about the problems besetting the 
Navy, is the story of just how Admiral Boorda's medals became a cause of concern for 
the news media.  After all, knowledge of campaign ribbons is not the sort of thing 
one expects of reporters.
<DD>It turns out that the medals story was fed to 
<I>Newsweek</I> and ABC News by a little-known outfit called the National 
Security News Service (NSNS).  A charter member of the blame-America-first 
chorus and an appendage of the anti-defense lobby, the Service delivers 
pre-packaged news stories to the media.  Such was 
the case with the account of Admiral Boorda's Vietnam decorations. 
<DD>Since the leg work is already done, the press naturally gobbles up these 
stories hook, line, and sinker.  The <I>Washington 
Post</I>, ABC's &quot;World News Tonight,&quot; 
and &quot;Prime Time Live&quot; have all used NSNS reports, all of which are hostile to the 
U.S. armed forces and invariably designed to denigrate the defense establishment.
<DD>Veteran activist Wayne T. Jaquith founded NSNS in 1990 as an adjunct 
of the Peoples Education Center.  Earlier, Jaquith had been executive director 
of another far-left group called Physicians for Social Responsibility, the 
American affiliate of International Physicians for the Prevention of Nuclear War  one 
of a number of groups used by the Soviet Union to undermine support for 
military preparedness in the West.  As the <I>Washington 
Times</I> reported on May 20, these groups were loosely tied to Soviet 
&quot;active measures&quot; and were conceived by then KGB head Yuri Andropov as a 
replacement for the nuclear-freeze movement, which had lost credibility as a 
result of its more direct ties to Soviet espionage.  Yevgeniy Chazov, health 
minister under Leonid Brezhnev, was the head of the international physicians group.
<DD>Apparently unhappy with the outcome of the cold war, NSNS seems 
determined to inflict revenge on the U.S. military that made the West's triumph 
possible.  Indeed, NSNS's bureau chief, Joseph J. Trento, a former CNN 
reporter, told the <I>Wall Street Journal</I> that 
now that Admiral Boorda is dead, &quot;What we're going to do is look to see if 
there was some other reason that Boorda felt exposed.&quot;
<DD>NSNS receives funding from liberal foundations, most prominently the 
W. Alton Jones Foundation, a supporter of sundry left-liberal causes.  Jaquith 
told <I>Organization Trends</I> that his group 
also receives funding from the John D. &amp; Catherine T. MacArthur 
Foundation, one of America's premier establishment philanthropies.  And he confirmed 
that it had received one grant from the Arca Foundation, which in the past was 
run by liberal gadfly Marge Tabankin, former head of the Hollywood Women's 
Political Caucus and current director of the Streisand Foundation.
<DD>The real story here is not the news service; it is what this tells us about 
the American media.  Groups like NSNS exist on the extreme fringe of the 
political spectrum.  Yet with little effort, they 
are able to sell their wares to unquestioning reporters.  The same reporters who 
would instinctively question the motives of anything prepared by a 
right-of-center think tank, are all too happy to serve 
as a conduit for NSNS's anti-military agenda, while affecting shock and 
disbelief at any suggestion of bias.

